results.title: Genuine sea glass keyring, stacked sea glass with live laugh love charm and fish clasp, beach lovers, sea glass collectors and surfers gift
results.description:
I've made this sea glass keyring by stacking little pieces of genuine beach found sea glass, then added a live laugh love charm and a fish clasp. A beautiful gift for beach lovers, sea glass collectors, or just for you, have beach vibes wherever you go. 

Stack of four sea glass pieces is 1.5 cm 

Silver coloured keyring is 3 cm round

The total hanging length is 9 cm

See more sea glass here https://www.etsy.com/au/shop/ItzOriginal?section_id=26340062

The fish clasp unclips so you can easily use this sea glass stack for anything you like. 

This a finished piece, you will receive this exact work as pictured, with a little hessian bag and pamphlet explaining my sea glass origins.   

“It is the nature of sea glass to have dimples, cracks, and chips, these are not faults they are part of the beauty.” I'm very fussy with the glass I use and place every piece with care. If it's there, it's because I thought it added something to the piece.

Your one of a kind sea glass creation is currently in my studio, ready to be shipped.

THINGS TO KNOW

*Your item will be safely packaged into a box for delivery, including literature explaining my sea glass finds in detail.

*Please read the FAQs for return policy

*Please note everything is handmade and therefore comes with its own imperfections and unique character.

*I do my best to show true colours but due to variations in computer monitors, there will be variations in colour depending on monitor settings and lighting.

* There is very little symmetry when working with genuine sea glass, therefore measurements although as accurate as I can be, are an approximation or an average of the uneven ups and downs.


---------------WHAT IS SEA GLASS?--------------- 

There is a mystery and a beauty about ‘genuine’ sea glass that is unlike anything else, it's the result of nature taking our rubbish and turning it into something beautiful. 

Sea glass comes from glass objects that somehow found their way into the ocean, here they are tossed and tumbled amongst the water and sand for sometimes as long as 100 years, to acquire their characteristic texture and shape. 

I’m lucky to find these pieces washed up onto the beach like little jewels. While beachcombing I also collect rubbish, so I’m cleaning up the beach and making art!
